# DHCP Lease Cycle Analysis

This lab traces a full DHCP lease cycle — Discover, Offer, Request, ACK — plus the ARP traffic a Windows host generates around it to check for address conflicts.

**1. Are DHCP messages sent over UDP or TCP?**

UDP. DHCP clients use UDP port 68, and DHCP servers use UDP port 67.

![DHCP packet list showing the Discover/Offer/Request/ACK exchange over UDP ports 67/68](images/fig-01.png)

**2. Diagram the DHCP Discover/Offer/Request/ACK exchange.**

```
Client (0.0.0.0:68)  --DHCP Discover-->  Server (192.168.1.1:67)
Server               --DHCP Offer----->  Client
Client               --DHCP Request-->   Server
Server               --DHCP ACK-------->  Client
```

Ports are the standard DHCP ports 67 (server) and 68 (client).

**3. What is the link-layer address of your host?**

`30:d0:42:xx:xx:xx`

**4. What values differentiate the Discover message from the Request message?**

The Request contains Option 50 (Requested IP Address `192.168.1.137`), Option 54 (DHCP Server Identifier `192.168.1.1`), and DHCP Message Type = Request — none of which appear in the Discover.

**5. What are the transaction IDs, and what is their purpose?**

- First exchange (Discover/Offer): `0x7befa33c`
- Second exchange (Request/ACK): `0x8fa4071a`

Transaction IDs tie the messages of a single DHCP conversation together so the client can match replies to its own requests.

**6. What are the source and destination IP addresses for each message?**

| Message | Source | Destination |
|---|---|---|
| Discover | 0.0.0.0 | 255.255.255.255 |
| Offer | 192.168.1.1 | 192.168.1.137 |
| Request | 0.0.0.0 | 255.255.255.255 |
| ACK | 192.168.1.1 | 192.168.1.137 |

![DHCP Offer packet detail showing source/destination IP addressing](images/fig-02.png)

**7. What is the IP address of the DHCP server?**

`192.168.1.1`

**8. What IP address is offered to the client?**

`192.168.1.137`

**9. Is a relay agent present?**

No. The Relay Agent IP field is `0.0.0.0`, indicating the client and server are on the same local network with no relay in between.

**10. What is the purpose of the router and subnet mask options returned by the server?**

The Router option identifies the default gateway (`192.168.1.1`); the Subnet Mask option (`255.255.255.0`) tells the client which addresses are on its local network versus which need to be routed.

**11. Did the client accept the offer?**

Yes — the client requested `192.168.1.137` in its Request message and received a DHCP ACK confirming the lease.

**12. What is the lease time?**

12 hours (43,200 seconds).

**13. What is the purpose of the DHCP Release message?**

It tells the server the client is voluntarily giving up its address so it can be reassigned immediately. If a client disconnects without sending Release (e.g., it loses power), the address simply remains reserved until the lease naturally expires.

![DHCP Release message from the client to the server](images/fig-03.png)

**14. Were any ARP packets observed around the DHCP exchange? Why?**

Yes — ARP Probes, an ARP Request, and an ARP Announcement were all observed. Windows uses ARP Probes before finalizing a new address to make sure no other device on the network is already using it (duplicate address detection), and follows up with a gratuitous ARP Announcement once the address is confirmed, so other devices on the LAN update their own ARP caches with its new mapping.

![ARP packet list showing ARP Probes, Request, and Announcement traffic around the DHCP lease](images/fig-04.png)
